        "answer_count": 2,
        "title": "Replacing an unknown pattern size with a character",
        "body": "<p>Is there a way to replace  a specific repetitive character using regular expressions?  <\/p>\n\n<p>Example:<br><\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>str = \"Anne has nnnn things\"<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>The solution would be: <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>\"Ane has n things\"<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>If a string has two or more instances of one character next to each other, the regular expression should replace them all with just one.<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 17107545,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "regex"
        ],
        "score": 0,
        "accepted_answer_id": 17107578,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 125,
        "last_edit_date": 1371213706
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/VjxwC.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 1101161,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1093528,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1093528/fge",
                "reputation": 122410,
                "display_name": "fge",
                "accept_rate": 65
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 7,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1371209802,
            "creation_date": 1371209802,
            "body": "<p>It is possible:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>inputString.replaceAll(\"(.)\\\\1+\", \"$1\")\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Match one character, capture it, repeat it once or more, replace with only the capture.<\/p>\n\n<p>However this may not be the faster solution. Such a thing is also doable with a simple loop:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public String removeRepetitions(final String input)\n{\n    if (input.isEmpty())\n        return input;\n\n    final int len = input.length();\n    final StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(length);\n\n    char current = input.charAt(0);\n    char c;\n    sb.append(current);\n\n    for (int i = 1; i &lt; len; i++) {\n        c = input.charAt(i);\n        if (c != current) {\n            sb.append(c);\n            current = c;\n        }\n    }\n\n    return sb.toString();\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 17107578,
            "question_id": 17107545
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d046efafc34567f8d4df7d1c6c37be40?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
